the switch for the main session, I should notify about this and potentially send a message to the main session to trigger its own switch. But first, let me check the memory files to see if they're up to date.\n\nActually, looking at the context-monitor.ps1 script more carefully - it just logs warnings but doesn't actually trigger a session switch. The actual switching happens when the main agent detects it's above threshold.\n\nThe cron job just monitors and alerts. The agentTurn mechanism is what actually creates the new session. Since this cron is running the context monitor script (not an agent that can do agentTurn), I should probably just update memory and let the main session handle the switch on its next run. But wait - the cron context monitor IS an isolated session. For a real seamless switch, the main session itself needs to trigger the switch.\n\nSince the main session is at 77% and I'm running in a cron context, I should:\n1. Update memory with current state\n2. The next time the main session runs, it should detect the high context and trigger the switch\n\nBut I can't effectively trigger a switch from this cron session. The real fix would be to have the main session detect this on its next turn. For now, let me just update memory and note this. But since this is a cron job, I should also check if there's something that needs to be done. Let me check memory for recent context.","thinkingSignature":"bd0ff837126246f0aaa43fedd663bb2e05b82dc3116e6fe8f604ede47f1f5421"},{"type":"text","text":"77% context on the main session (董事长's Feishu session). Let me check memory state and trigger a switch.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_tbqti3pn9qmh_1","name":"memory_search","arguments":{"query":"current task state session","maxResults":3}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_tbqti3pn9qmh_2","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Administrator\\.openclaw\\workspace\\MEMORY.md","limit":50}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"Min