{"type":"message","id":"fe81c66e","parentId":"c6f4caf0","timestamp":"2026-03-19T18:16:14.889Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Memory search is unavailable. Let me check if the main session needs a switch. The context is at 77% which is above the 60% threshold.\n\nLooking at the MEMORY.md, I see recent activity including OpenClaw configuration and skill installations.\n\nThe main session is at 77% - I should trigger a session switch. But since this cron session can't directly trigger a switch for the main session (agent:main:main), I need to think about what to do.\n\nActually, looking at the context-manager skill again:\n- It says the switch should happen automatically when the main session detects it's above threshold\n- The cron job just monitors\n\nBut the cron job is detecting 77% on the main session, which means the main session should have already triggered a switch. Maybe it's not detecting properly?\n\nLet me think about what I can do from this cron session:\n1. I can't directly trigger a switch for another session\n2. I could potentially send a message to the main session to trigger it\n3. I could update memory so the next session has context\n\nThe best approach would be:\n1. Update memory with current state\n2. Send a message to the main session to prompt it to switch\n\nWait - looking at the sessions list, the main session (`agent:main:main`) last ran at 1773942818463 (about 22 minutes ago based on current time 1773944100027). The session might still be responsive.\n\nActually, I realize I should just do the automatic thing - trigger an agentTurn session switch. But that's for the cron session to create a new isolated session, not to switch the main user session.\n\nThe real issue: The main session (董事长's Feishu session) is at 77%. When 董事长 sends a message, the main session will respond and could potentially go over limit. But it won't trigger a switch mid-conversation.\n\nWhat I should do:\n1. Since this is a cron monitor, it just alerts\n\n\n2. The automatic switch would happen when the main agent itself detects it's above threshold on a new turn\n3. For now, I'll just log this and let the system handle it naturally\n\nBut the context manager skill says \"零操作\" - fully automatic. Maybe the main agent should already have triggered a switch. Let me check if there's a recent session that already did the switch...\n\nLooking at the sessions again, there's no recent session switch. The main session is still at 77%.\n\nActually, thinking about this more carefully - the cron context monitor is meant to be run periodically and when it detects high usage, it should trigger a switch via agent\n\nTurn. The issue is the script just logs a warning - it doesn't actually trigger anything.\n\nFor a proper implementation, I would need to either:\n1. Have the main session self-switch (internal detection)\n2. Have this cron monitor trigger an agentTurn that then does the switch\n\nSince the cron session can spawn subagents, maybe I should spawn one to handle the switch? But the switch needs to happen in the context of the main session with full memory.\n\nActually, the right approach is simpler: just let the main session handle it naturally. When 董事长 sends the next message, the main session will be at 77% and could trigger a switch. But that requires the main agent to be smart about this.\n\nThe cron job running the context-monitor.ps1 script can't directly cause the switch - it just monitors. A real implementation would need the main agent to check its context at the start of each turn. Since I can't modify that from here, I'll update memory with current state and let the natural flow handle it.","thinkingSignature":"d9aec22ca70d5927408073ce978c0bd9b4f145b60b86c01b16353fd052055b15"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_sfte2osr37do_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Administrator\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\2026-03-20.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax"