{"type":"message","id":"9bb99295","parentId":"b94820e3","timestamp":"2026-03-19T18:16:36.113Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see there's already a memory entry from 02:10 AM today showing context at 77%. This confirms the issue persists. The monitor keeps triggering every 5 minutes.\n\nThe main session is at 77% - since I can't directly trigger a switch from this cron session, and the switch needs to happen in the main session context, the best I can do is:\n\n1. Note that context is still at 77% (persistent high)\n2. The automatic switch should happen when the main session responds to 董事长's next message\n\nBut wait - looking at the context manager skill more carefully, it says the switch is triggered via agentTurn. The cron session creates an isolated agentTurn session which then takes over. But that would be a NEW isolated session, not the main session.\n\nActually I think I'm overcomplicating this. The skill design is:\n1. Cron monitor detects high context\n2. Cron triggers agentTurn to create new isolated session\n3. The new isolated session loads memory and continues work\n4. The old session is abandoned\n\nBut the issue is: the main session (agent:main:main) is the one talking to 董事长. If we create a new isolated session, it won't be the one talking to 董事长 unless the delivery is set up correctly.\n\nLooking at the skill again:\n```json\n{\n  \"kind\": \"agentTurn\",\n  \"message\": \"【无缝接续】请从MEMORY.md加载完整记忆，自然继续对话...\",\n  \"deliver\": true,\n  \"channel\": \"qqbot\", \n  \"to\": \"USER_ID\"\n}\n```\n\nIt uses `deliver: true` and specifies channel + to. So the new session would deliver to the user directly. This means a NEW session would be created and it would talk to 董事长 directly, while the old high-context session is abandoned.\n\nBut this cron session (agent:main:cron:696799cb) is NOT the main session. It's running the context monitor. To trigger a proper switch, I would need to:\n\n\n1. Spawn an agentTurn from THIS cron session\n2. That agentTurn creates a new isolated session\n3. The new session delivers to 董事长\n\nThe problem is I don't have the full context of what 董事长 was discussing - the memory files may not have everything. The real automatic switch should happen when the main session itself detects it's above threshold and triggers agentTurn. But that requires the main agent to do this check at startup or at each turn, which may not be happening.\n\nSince this cron is just a monitoring job and the main session doesn't seem to be self-switching, I should just log the persistent high context and let it be. The cron keeps firing every 5 minutes and logging warnings.\n\nLooking at the session list, the main session is at 77% and it's been this way since at least 02:10 AM. The cron job is being triggered but it's not actually fixing the issue. The script just logs a warning. What I could do is spawn a subagent from this cron session to trigger an agentTurn to create a new session for 董事长. But I'd need to know what 董事长 wants to continue discussing.\n\nThe safest approach is to just update the memory log showing persistent high context at 77% across multiple checks (02:10 and 02:15), note that the main session needs attention, and let the system handle it naturally. The cron keeps firing every 5 minutes, which suggests the automatic switch mechanism isn't working as intended, but creating a new session without full context could cause more problems than it solves.","thinkingSignature":"ee94290c0059114790c69a5fb2506ee1b9fbd854b81bc254209e7b0ee3580585"},{"type":"text","text":"Persistent high context at 77% across checks. The main session for 董事长 hasn't self-switched. Let me update the daily log and attempt a session switch:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vx5huy00inbj_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Administrator\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\2026-03-20.md","old_string":"# 2026-03-20 Daily Memory\n\n## Context Monitor Alerts\n- 02:10 — Context usag